<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Manifests</strong> standardizes <strong>machine-readable project and release metadata</strong> —
    the structured descriptors that let tooling reason about a module without reading its source or a prose
    changelog. Its first protocol is the
    <a href="#protocol-changelog-manifest">Changelog Manifest</a>: a per-release, per-module description of
    <em>what changed and how breaking it is</em>, with the migration that mechanically applies each breaking
    change. It is the contract that makes safe <strong>auto-update</strong> possible.
  </p>
  <p>
    A human <code>CHANGELOG.md</code> cannot be acted on by a machine. The Changelog Manifest is the
    <strong>dual</strong> of it: a readable summary for people <em>and</em> a typed API for tools. The
    <a href="/backlog/101-auto-update-pipeline/">auto-update pipeline (#101)</a> reads it to classify an
    update's risk, the <a href="/backlog/094-ai-upgrader-tools/">upgraders (#094)</a> read it to apply bundled
    codemods without hand-editing call sites, and <a href="/backlog/103-incremental-delivery/">incremental
    delivery (#103)</a> reads it to compute exactly which modules moved.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #047857; font-size: 1rem;">Borrow the human layer; standardize only the machine layer</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      The Changelog Manifest does <strong>not</strong> invent a versioning vocabulary. The human-readable
      surface reuses <a href="https://keepachangelog.com/">Keep a Changelog</a> sections and
      <a href="https://www.conventionalcommits.org/">Conventional Commits</a> types; the change-severity
      vocabulary is <a href="https://semver.org/">semver</a> verbatim (<code>major</code> / <code>minor</code> /
      <code>patch</code>). What is <em>new</em>, and all this standard actually defines, is the
      <strong>machine schema</strong> — per-module entries keyed to a severity and a migration reference — and
      the <strong>migration-script linkage</strong> that turns a breaking change into an executable codemod.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

