<section id="how" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h3>
  <p>
    A release publishes one manifest. Each entry names a module, its change severity and type, a human
    summary, and — when the change is breaking — a reference to the migration that applies it. Tools read
    the manifest; they never parse prose.
  </p>
  {% highlight "json" %}
{
  "manifestVersion": "1",
  "package": "@frontierui/droplist",
  "release": "3.0.0",
  "previous": "2.4.1",
  "entries": [
    {
      "module": "blocks/droplist/AutoComplete.ts",
      "severity": "major",
      "type": "changed",
      "summary": "`filter` prop renamed to `filterStrategy`.",
      "migration": {
        "ref": "migrations/3.0.0/rename-filter-prop.codemod.ts",
        "author": "frontierui",
        "integrity": "sha256-…",
        "rewrites": "consumer call sites of <auto-complete filter>"
      }
    },
    {
      "module": "blocks/droplist/Filter.ts",
      "severity": "patch",
      "type": "fixed",
      "summary": "Diacritic folding now matches `Intl.Collator` sensitivity."
    }
  ]
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <p>
    The updater derives the package bump from the strictest entry severity (one <code>major</code> entry makes
    the release <code>major</code>), routes the breaking entries through their migrations, and — for a clean
    update — applies them without a human editing a single call site.
  </p>
</section>

<section id="protocol-changelog-manifest" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="changelog-manifest-protocol">Changelog Manifest Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for a release's machine-readable change description. A conformant manifest is a dual
    artifact: a <strong>human-readable</strong> projection (Keep a Changelog sections) and a
    <strong>machine schema</strong> (the typed entries above). The protocol standardizes <em>only</em> the
    machine schema and the migration linkage; the human layer is a rendering of the same entries and borrows
    existing vocabulary rather than defining one.
  </p>

  <h4 id="schema-contract">Schema Contract</h4>
  <p>The novel, standardized surface — every conformant manifest entry satisfies this shape:</p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
type Severity = 'major' | 'minor' | 'patch';            // semver, verbatim
type ChangeType =                                        // Keep a Changelog vocabulary
    'added' | 'changed' | 'deprecated' | 'removed' | 'fixed' | 'security';

interface ChangelogEntry {
    // The unit is the module/file, never the whole package.
    module: string;
    severity: Severity;
    type: ChangeType;
    // The human half of the dual format.
    summary: string;
    // Present iff the change is breaking and mechanically applicable.
    migration?: MigrationRef;
}

interface MigrationRef {
    // The codemod that applies this breaking change to consumer source.
    ref: string;
    // Trust metadata — a migration runs on the consumer's code (#101 security step).
    author: string;
    integrity: string;           // content hash of the referenced codemod
    rewrites: string;            // human description of the scope it touches
}

interface ChangelogManifest {
    manifestVersion: string;
    package: string;
    release: string;             // the new version (semver)
    previous: string;           // the version this manifest migrates from
    entries: ChangelogEntry[];
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="severity-derivation">Severity Derivation</h4>
  <p>
    The package's release severity is the <strong>strictest entry severity</strong>: any <code>major</code>
    entry makes the release <code>major</code>; otherwise any <code>minor</code> makes it <code>minor</code>;
    else <code>patch</code>. This makes semver a <em>derived</em> fact of the per-module entries, not a
    hand-asserted label — the same strictest-wins reduction the
    <a href="/projects/webvalidation/#protocol-validation">Validation Protocol</a> uses for merged validity.
  </p>

  <h4 id="migration-trust">Migration Trust</h4>
  <p>
    A migration is executable code that rewrites the <em>consumer's</em> source, so it is the manifest's one
    security-sensitive surface. The protocol requires every <code>MigrationRef</code> to carry an
    <code>integrity</code> hash of the referenced codemod and an <code>author</code>, so the
    <a href="/backlog/101-auto-update-pipeline/">auto-update pipeline (#101)</a> can verify a migration before
    running it and refuse one whose hash does not match. The protocol defines the <em>linkage and trust
    fields</em>; how a codemod is authored and how trust is established is the pipeline's security step, not
    this schema's.
  </p>

